liveUpdates.author: Richard Fausset
liveUpdates.text: Youngkin’s showing tonight is of interest to two possible Georgia governor’s candidates, Democrat Stacey Abrams and Republican David Perdue — who, like Youngkin, might seek to unite pro- and anti-Trump G.O.P. factions.

liveUpdates.author: Dana Rubinstein
liveUpdates.text: Alvin Bragg will become Manhattan’s first Black district attorney, according to the Associated Press. He will inherit a high-profile case against former President Donald J. Trump.

liveUpdates.author: Jeff Mays
liveUpdates.text: “We won,” shouted an Eric Adams staffer from the stage just 17 minutes after the polls closed in New York City.

liveUpdates.author: Dana Rubinstein
liveUpdates.text: The polls have closed in New York City. We will know the outcome of the mayor’s race, and several down-ballot races, soon.

liveUpdates.author: Jeremy W. Peters
liveUpdates.text: If Youngkin prevails, expect the two warring factions of the G.O.P. to both declare victory. "Never Trumpers" will claim this shows there’s a path without him. And Trump supporters will say he dragged Youngkin over the line.

liveUpdates.author: Shane Goldmacher
liveUpdates.text: McAuliffe is far underperforming his 2013 showing in rural and white parts of southwestern Virginia — by as much as 20 percentage points in some places.

liveUpdates.author: Melissa Lyttle
liveUpdates.text: Mike Stoddard of Herndon, Va., watching results on a big screen at a Glenn Youngkin watch party in Chantilly: “Financially, emotionally, spiritually, I think he’s just trying to get veterans and Virginians back on track.”
liveUpdates.image_credit: Melissa Lyttle for The New York Times

liveUpdates.author: Jeremy W. Peters
liveUpdates.text: In heavily blue Fairfax County, the early and absentee results so far, roughly 75-25 for McAuliffe, is where Republicans think they need to be if this is going to be close.

liveUpdates.author: Timothy Arango
liveUpdates.text: In Minneapolis, Democrats are divided over a charter amendment to replace the Police Department. Progressives – like Rep. Ilhan Omar – have been vocal in support. Moderates like Sen. Amy Klobuchar oppose the measure but have not campaigned against it.

liveUpdates.author: Reid Epstein
liveUpdates.text: In Lexington, Va., where Joe Biden won 65 percent of the vote, Terry McAuliffe is at just 50 percent with about half the vote counted so far. It’s a good representation of how far behind Biden McAuliffe is running in tonight’s results.

liveUpdates.author: Doug Mills
liveUpdates.text: At a watch party for Terry McAuliffe in in Fairfax, Va., supporters checked their laptops to see the early return numbers.

liveUpdates.author: Nate Cohn
liveUpdates.text: McAuliffe is ever so slightly underperforming. The latest example is Fairfax: McAuliffe is at 74 percent of the advance vote, but our estimate was that he needed 76 percent. It’s early and not much, but it’s starting to add up.

liveUpdates.author: Tracey Tully
liveUpdates.text: Gov. Phil Murphy’s supporters are filing into Asbury Park’s Convention Hall in New Jersey, the same place he celebrated his 2017 win.

liveUpdates.author: Tracey Tully
liveUpdates.text: A judge rejected a request to keep polls open in New Jersey until 9:30 p.m. He said it would cause disarray, and there’s no proof that voters were turned away because of snags with the new electronic poll books.

liveUpdates.author: Nate Cohn
liveUpdates.text: Youngkin has an early lead in Virginia. That may be deceptive. So far, we mainly have heavily Republican Election Day vote. Over all, 12 percent of Election Day votes have been counted by the state, compared to just 5 percent of early and 2 percent of absentee votes.

liveUpdates.author: Nate Cohn
liveUpdates.text: It’s early, but so far more than 100 precincts have reported in Virginia and they’re generally consistent with a highly competitive race with a very high turnout.
liveUpdates.image_credit: Melissa Lyttle for The New York Times

liveUpdates.author: Richard Fausset
liveUpdates.text: In Atlanta, a runoff is likely in this crowded mayor’s race. Mayor Kasim Reed and council president Felicia Moore have polled well. A wildcard: Andre Dickens, a critic of Reed’s.

liveUpdates.author: Trip Gabriel
liveUpdates.text: Democratic strategists in Chesterfield County last week told me they did not expect McAuliffe to win there, even though Biden carried the traditionally conservative region.

liveUpdates.author: Jeff Mays
liveUpdates.text: All is quiet here at the New York Marriott where Eric Adams is set to hold his election night party. “I think we’re going to win,” joked one adviser to the likely next mayor.

liveUpdates.author: Jennifer Medina
liveUpdates.text: Republicans tried to make critical race theory a central part of the Virginia governor’s race, but parents’ anger over schools may have had more to do with pandemic shutdowns.

liveUpdates.author: Reid Epstein
liveUpdates.text: Fairfax is usually among Virginia’s last counties to report final results in statewide elections and has in past elections given Democratic candidates a boost at the end of election nights.
liveUpdates.image_credit: Kenny Holston for The New York Times

liveUpdates.author: Reid Epstein
liveUpdates.text: Fairfax County is delayed in reporting its early vote ballots. We do not know when we are expecting those ballots to be counted, but it will not be by the self-imposed 8 p.m. deadline.

liveUpdates.author: Nate Cohn
liveUpdates.text: For Youngkin to win, he’s going to need it all: a favorable turnout and gains across the state. But there are two big counties he all but must flip back: Virginia Beach and Chesterfield, outside Richmond.

liveUpdates.author: Shane Goldmacher
liveUpdates.text: In the final tally, $66.3 million was spent on television ads in the Virginia governor’s race general election, according to AdImpact. Democrats spent more: $34.6 million to $31.7 million.

liveUpdates.author: Richard Fausset
liveUpdates.text: In Atlanta, the focus is on former Mayor Kasim Reed, a familiar figure burdened by his administration’s scandals. The question is whether his high name recognition will trump high negatives.
liveUpdates.image_credit: Kendrick Brinson for The New York Times

liveUpdates.author: Nate Cohn
liveUpdates.text: Democrats might jump to an early lead in Virginia, where counties are now allowed to pre-process absentee votes. That should allow for quick reporting of votes that are expected to be heavily Democratic.

liveUpdates.author: Dana Rubinstein
liveUpdates.text: Polls close in New York City in about two hours. Anecdotally, turnout appears low, which is unlikely to affect the outcome of the mayor’s race. But it could affect some down-ballot contests.

liveUpdates.author: Timothy Arango
liveUpdates.text: Minneapolis recorded the most homicides since the mid-1990s last year. As voters weigh whether to replace the city's police department, many are caught between two beliefs — that policing needs to be drastically reformed, and that more policing is needed to confront the surge in gun violence.

liveUpdates.author: Ellen Barry
liveUpdates.text: Many Boston voters cited the need for affordable housing. “A lot of people realize they won’t be able to live in this city in 10 years if this continues,” said Andrew Conant, 28.

liveUpdates.author: Jennifer Medina
liveUpdates.text: When voting began this morning, nearly 1.2 million Virginians had already cast ballots. By comparison, 2.6 million voters turned out in 2017, the last time the state picked its governor.

liveUpdates.author: Shane Goldmacher
liveUpdates.text: There are several interesting mayor’s races nationwide that pit more progressive versus more moderate Democrats, including in Boston, Seattle, Cleveland, Minneapolis and Buffalo

liveUpdates.author: Timothy Arango
liveUpdates.text: Minneapolis will decide whether to keep or replace its long-troubled Police Department. I’m interested to see returns in North Minneapolis, which has high rates of gun violence and where many people want more police.

liveUpdates.author: Trip Gabriel
liveUpdates.text: In Richmond, Va., a deep blue city, voters found many ways to say they’re nervous: “I’m really on pins and needles.’’ “I was hoping we’d be up by a higher margin.” “My anxiety level is high.”

liveUpdates.author: Tracey Tully
liveUpdates.text: Concerns about voter turnout in New Jersey already had both campaigns for governor in overdrive. Then there were reports of tech snags that led to lines of frustrated voters.

liveUpdates.author: Jeremy W. Peters
liveUpdates.text: Youngkin has managed to keep Trump at an arm’s length. If he wins, “Never Trump’’ Republicans and moderates will argue that Virginia is their new template. And Trump will likely claim victory.

liveUpdates.author: Nate Cohn
liveUpdates.text: There are signs of high turnout in Virginia, but not many clues about who may benefit. High turnout is assumed to help Democrats, but Republicans stand to gain if more white, working class voters go to the polls.

liveUpdates.author: Astead W. Herndon
liveUpdates.text: An old enemy is threatening the final hours of voting in Virginia: weather. Officials are eyeing increasing chances of rain and lightning in some of the state’s metro areas.
liveUpdates.image_credit: Melissa Lyttle for The New York Times

liveUpdates.author: Dana Rubinstein
liveUpdates.text: The contest between Eric Adams and Curtis Sliwa is something of a fait accompli. In New York City, where Democrats far outnumber Republicans, Adams is expected to win. The question is, by how much.

liveUpdates.author: Ellen Barry
liveUpdates.text: Progressives in Boston have been galvanized by Michelle Wu’s ambitious proposals, like rent control and fare-free public transit. But other voters expressed skepticism that Wu could deliver, and said this has swayed them to Annissa Essaibi George. “I know Michelle believes she can do all these things,” said Edward Ake, 48, an immigrant from Cameroon. “But it’s not going to happen. I’m sorry to say it so bluntly.”
liveUpdates.image_credit: Philip Keith for The New York Times

liveUpdates.author: Ellen Barry
liveUpdates.text: Boston will elect a woman to be mayor for the first time. The candidates are city councilors Annissa Essaibi George, a former schoolteacher, and Michelle Wu, who has galvanized young progressives.
liveUpdates.image_credit: Philip Keith for The New York Times

liveUpdates.author: Jeff Mays
liveUpdates.text: New York City residents are poised to elect Eric Adams as the second Black mayor and Alvin Bragg as the first Black district attorney of Manhattan. Follow our updates.
